      "url": "https://www.themarginalian.org/2026/05/21/penguin/",
      "title": "[The Marginalian] How Evolution Invented Faith: The Patience of the Penguin and the Art of Withstanding Abandonment",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://www.themarginalian.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/penguins.jpg?fit=1200%2C631&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://www.themarginalian.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/penguins.jpg?fit=1200%2C631&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n&#8220;Let us love this distance which is wholly woven of friendship, for those who do not love each other are not separated,&#8221; Simone Weil wrote in her soulful meditation on the paradox of closeness and separation. To be separated from a loved one &#8212; in space or in silence, by choice or by circumstance &#8212; is a singularly discomposing experience. It takes a tremendous effort of the psyche to keep oneself from feeling abandoned, and we know from fMRI studies that every abandonment is experienced as a miniature death because the brain registers a loved one&#8217;s death &#8212; the ultimate&#8230;&#160;<a class=\"h3 read_on\" href=\"https://www.themarginalian.org/2026/05/21/penguin/\">read&#160;article</a>",
      "date_published": "2026-05-21T19:54:50+00:00",
      "authors": [
        {
          "name": "The Marginalian",
          "url": "https://www.themarginalian.org"
        }
      ],
      "image": "https://www.themarginalian.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/penguins.jpg?fit=1200%2C631&ssl=1",
      "_score": 22
    },
